This tiny dormouse cheated death after he fell out of his mother’s nest and was almost stepped on by a passerby.

The cute creature found himself stranded on the kerb of a pavement just inches from a busy road when the member of the public walked past.

The helpless baby rodent, which was about three weeks old, had no way of finding his family and was at risk from the cold weather when the kind-hearted person picked him up.

Lucky: Centre supervisor Antonia Blacker with Douglas the dormouse who fell out of his mother's nest

He was taken to the Folly Wildlife Rescue near Tunbridge Wells, Kent, where staff named him ‘Douglas’ and worked around the clock to save his life.

They put him in an incubator and fed him Farley’s Rusks and a milk formula every two hours until he built his strength up.

Douglas was less than an inch long when he arrived at the rescue centre and will reach up to 3.5 inches when fully grown.

Annette Risley, centre manager at Folly Wildlife said: 'He was found on a pavement on his own by a member of the public.

